{
  "texts": [
    "In the second phase, we summarized these notes into general patterns and trends, and identified consistent and inconsistent examples in the data.",
    "ResultsResults are divided into four sections: We present the results of fine-tuned GLMs on AES and ASAS in the first two sections, respectively; we characterize feedback after prompting GLMs to explain their scores based on item-specific rubrics for AES and ASAS in the next two sections, respectively.",
    "Automated Essay ScoringTable 4 presents the results of fine-tuned GLMs on performing AES on the ASAP-AES dataset.",
    "We provide comparisons to several notable benchmarks pertinent to the task.",
    "These include the original human-human agreement score reported by Shermis (2014), the BoW results reported by Taghipour & Ng (2016) and subsequent modifications using attention mechanisms (Dong et al., 2017), the original BERT results from Rodriguez et al. ( 2019), the current SOTA performance (J. Xie et al., 2022), \"fine-tuned\" GPT-3.5 (Mansour et al., 2024), and GPT-4 (Xiao et al., 2024)."
  ]
